data.name: Apollo Control Sensor
data.description:
This sensor is required for a vehicle to subscribe to the control topic of Apollo. This sensor also demonstrates how a user can check when SVL Simulator receives the first control message from the AD stack like Apollo. Based on this time, you can start the rest of the simulation or do some other interesting things.
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#apollo-control for more details.

data.name: Apollo Perception Visualizer 3D Sensor
data.description:
This sensor will visualize bounding boxes on objects as detected by Apollo Stack. It does not publish any data and instead subscribes to a topic from Apollo perception module. The color of the boxes are:
	[
		"Car": "Green"
		"Pedestrian": "Yellow"
		"Bicycle": "Cyan"
		"Unknown":  "Magenta"
	]
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#apollo-perception-visualizer-3d for more details.

data.name: CAN Bus Sensor
data.description:
This sensor sends data about the vehicle chassis. The data includes:
	* Speed [m/s]
	* Throttle [%]
	* Braking [%]
	* Steering [+/- %]
	* Parking Brake Status [bool]
	* High Beam Status [bool]
	* Low Beam Status [bool]
	* Hazard Light Status [bool]
	* Fog Light Status [bool]
	* Left Turn Signal Status [bool]
	* Right Turn Signal Status [bool]
	* Wiper Status [bool]
	* Reverse Gear Status [bool]
	* Selected Gear [Int]
	* Engine Status [bool]
	* Engine RPM [RPM]
	* GPS Latitude [Latitude]
	* GPS Longitude [Longitude]
	* Altitude [m]
	* Orientation [3D Vector of Euler angles]
	* Velocity [3D Vector of m/s]
See https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/sensors-list/#can-bus for more details.

data.name: Differential Drive Control Sensor
data.description:
The **Differential Drive Control** plugin provides a means for driving differential drive robots (ego) vehicles. Differential drive is a drive mechanism commonly used in mobile robots where two wheels are mounted on a common axis and each is capable of being driven forward or backward independently.

Differential drive robots often have wheel encoders that precisely track the rotation of each wheel. The rotation of each wheel can be used both as feedback for a closed loop controller to precisely control the robot motion, and for dead reckoning.

For more details, check: <https://www.svlsimulator.com/docs/simulation-content/differential-drive-control>

data.name: ROS2ForUnitySVLBridge
data.description:
ROS2 For Unity svl bridge by Robotec.ai

If you are using this plugin with ADE image in Autoware.Auto (https://www.autoware.org/) project then you are good to go and don't need to do anything. Otherwise, you have to prepare your SVL simulator:

IMPORTANT #1: This bridge requires additional binaries based on your ROS2 and OS versions. Go to https://github.com/RobotecAI/ROS2ForUnity/releases to download required archive, then extract its contents to SVL simulator:
1. libraries from `Plugins/<OS_NAME>/x86_64/*` put into `simulator_Data/Plugins` of svl simulator directory,
2. libraries from `Plugins/*.dll` put into `simulator_Data/Managed` of svl simulator directory.

IMPORTANT #2: In order for plugin to work, you have to also set "LD_LIBRARY_PATH" points to " <APP>/simulator_Data/Plugins" folder.

IMPORTANT #3: You must have your ROS2 environment sourced before running application.

This is native ROS2 bridge implementation based on ros2-for-unity project: https://github.com/RobotecAI/ros2-for-unity

Source code: https://github.com/RobotecAI/ROS2ForUnity

data.name: Line Distance Sensor
data.description:
It will show distance(in 3D) from where it placed to line. Border lines and lanes need to be annotated for it to work. 
Didn't optimize it, or calculate its performance, so there might or might not be some performance backlash for cpu. 
It loops all lanes and then loops closest lane's lines inside single update call in order to find its distance to closest line segment.
